<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-11T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-11T02:00:00-05:00" n="71" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d71">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1343: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-11T15:00:00+08:00">March 11, 1935—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 11—7:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>113. Legation’s 109, March 7, 5 p.m., regarding Shanghai defense scheme.
                            Consulate General reports that question of consultative consular
                            representation has been taken up orally without definite results. Both
                            matters will receive further attention upon return to Shanghai of
                            Colonel Beaumont<note n="61" xml:id="d71fn61">Col. John C. Beaumont,
                                commanding the 4th U. S. Marine Regiment at Shanghai.</note> who is
                            now in Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>